  <static seed="1442" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions6.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{9+\frac{1}{q-10}}}{{\frac{1}{q-10}-\frac{1}{7}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{7\mathopen{}\left(9q-89\right)}{-q+17}, q\ne 10</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{9+\frac{1}{q-10}}}{{\frac{1}{q-10}-\frac{1}{7}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{9+\frac{1}{q-10}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{q-10}-\frac{1}{7}}</m>, which is <m>{7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{9+\frac{1}{q-10}}}{{\frac{1}{q-10}-\frac{1}{7}}} \amp = \frac{({9+\frac{1}{q-10}})\cdot{7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)}}{({\frac{1}{q-10}-\frac{1}{7}})\cdot{7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{9\cdot 7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)+\frac{1}{q-10}\cdot 7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)}}{{\frac{1}{q-10}\cdot 7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)-\frac{1}{7}\cdot 7\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{63\mathopen{}\left(q-10\right)+7}}{{7-\left(q-10\right)}} , q\ne10 \\
    \amp = \frac{{63q-630+7}}{{7-q+10}}, q\ne10  \\
    \amp = \frac{{63q-623}}{{17-q}}, q\ne10 \\
    \amp = {\frac{7\mathopen{}\left(9q-89\right)}{-q+17}, q\ne 10}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factors <m>q-10</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the simplification is <m>q \ne 10</m>.</p>
</solution>
